@NODE asin "Previous area"
Pushing this button takes you to the previous area. The area list is
circular, so pushing this button when in the first area it will take you
to the last one.

Keyboard shortcut: q
@ENDNODE

@NODE ades "Next area"
Pushing this button takes you to the next area. The area list is
circular, so pushing this button when in the last area it will take you
to the first one.

Keyboard shortcut: w
@ENDNODE

@NODE ades2 "Next area with unread messages"
Pushing this button will take you to the next area containing messages
which have not been read yet.

Keyboard shortcut: e
@ENDNODE

@NODE treecomm "Tree mode commands"
Tree mode commands allow you to easily follow a thread concerning a
particular subject. Left to right (keyboard shortcuts are in parentheses):

(t) - List messages in thread. The messages shown in italic are those which
      have not been read, the underlined one is the current message and the bold ones
      are the marked messages. Simply double-click on a message to move
      to it.

(8) - Father of the current message.

(2) - Logical reading: goes to the next message of the thread performing a
      preorder visit of the message tree. When a thread is over go to the
      next.

(4) - Go to next thread.

(6) - Go to previous thread.

(+) - Logical reading like the third command, but only shows unread
      messages.
      @{B}This command is often sufficient to easily read a group of messages.@{UB}
@ENDNODE

@NODE seqcomm "Sequential commands"
Left to right (keyboard shortcuts are in parentheses):

(l) - Lists all messages in the area. The messages shown in italic are those which
      have not been read, the underlined one is the current message and the bold ones
      are the marked messages. Simply double-click on a message to move to
      it.

(ň) - Previous message. (also left cursor key)

(ŕ) - Next message. (also right cursor key)

(ů) - First message not read.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_label_2 "BBS configuration"
The listview contains the list of configured BBS's. If one of them is
selected, the gadgets on the right will be updated.

To add a BBS write its name in the string gadget beneath the listview and
press ENTER. To remove one click on its name in the listview and press
the REMOVE button.

On the right are two string gadgets, each one with a pop-up file requester
and a key for configuration. They are:

- @{i}Import filter: @{ui}Tells Bomb! which filter should be used when
  importing messages.

- @{i}Export filter: @{ui}Tells Bomb! which filter should be used when
  exporting messages.

Refer to the descriptions of individual filters to learn more about its
configuration (see @{"Supported filters" link filtri}.

The checkmark and the string field labeled as @{i}Automatic import@{ui} are
respectively used to activate the @{"automatic import" link autoimport} of messages
and to insert the name of the filter to identify the file to be imported.

The checkmark labeled as @{i}Max messages hysteresis@{ui} activates hysteresis in
@{"message deletion" link cancellazione}. The value of the hysteresis is set through the
slider on its right.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_label_4 "BBS" Lista delle BBS
This causes the BBS list to appear. Right of this button is the name of the
current BBS.

The listview which opens contains the list of all configured BBS's. Simply
double-click on one of them to move into its message base.

@{B}Remember that, in Bomb!, 'BBS' means any message source: it can be a real
BBS, but also an electronic mailbox or a USENET news server.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_label_5 "Aree"
This causes the area list to appear. Right of this button is the name of the
current area.

The listview which opens contains the list of the areas in the current BBS.
You can move to any of them double-clicking its name. If the name is in
boldface, this means that the area contains messages which have not been
read yet. Near the area names appear the number of messages contained in
the area and the number of unread messages.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_label_6 "Write message"
This window opens either by pressing @{b}New@{ub} or @{b}Reply@{ub}. If
@{b}Reply@{ub} was pressed, some string fields are initialized accordingly.

This window contains:

- A string field @{i}To:@{ui} in which the message addressee must be inserted.
  Clicking the list button will bring up a window containing a
  @{"user list" link lista}: you may choose a single addressee or multiple
  addressees. In the latter case, the @{i}Copies@{ui} checkmark will be
  set; resetting it will again send the message to a single addressee.

  See @{"User list configuration" link WI_label_17} for further details.

- A string field @{i}Subject:@{ui} where the message title must be written.

- A string field @{i}Area:@{ui} which initially should contain the name of the
  current area. Clicking the list button will bring up a window containing
  an area list: simply double-click on an area to select it as the new area
  for the message.
  @{b}Note:@{ub} In some cases (internet e-mail) this field can have no
  meaning (and no effect).

- A checkmark @{i}PVT@{ui} to send the message to the private mailbox (in this case
  the area name will be ghosted).
  This field has effect only in a BBS which handles private mailboxes.

- A cycle gadget to switch between @{i}New message@{ui} and @{i}Reply@{ui}.

- A @{i}Quoting@{ui} checkmark which enables quoting of the current message:
  the rows of the message which have previously been selected in the main
  window will be quoted and sent to the editor. This checkmark is always set when the window opens.
  Note that you can select multiple blocks of lines using the shift key.
  Between each pair of blocks the sniptext string defined in the
  @{"global settings" link WI_label_18} will be inserted.

- An @{i}All@{ui} checkmark: When selected, all the message will be quoted.
  When the window opens, this checkmark is set if less than 2 lines were
  selected.

- A @{i}Heading@{ui} checkmark, which automatically adds a heading to the
  message if the heading file was configured in the area settings window.
  See @{"Automatic heading" link intestazione} to know more about the format
  of this file.

- A string field with two buttons, @{i}Tagline@{ui} and @{i}Random@{ui}. Clicking on @{i}Tagline@{ui}
  will cause the @{"tagline window" link WI_label_16} to open. Clicking on @{i}Random@{ui} will choose
  a random tagline without opening any window.

  @{b}Note:@{ub} These buttons only work if in their area settings the
  Tagline gadget contains the name of a file containing taglines in the
  right @{"format" link fortag}.

- An @{"UUencode" link UUencode} checkmark with a string field. If this checkmark
  is selected, an UUencoded file can be added to the message; this file can
  be chosen via the string field nearby.

- Four checkmarks to handle @{"PGP" link criptazione} encrypting, which allow you
  to encrypt and/or sign a message, and to add your public key to it.
@ENDNODE

