The @{i}Working directory@{ui} string gadget contains the name of the
directory where Bomb! will keep its temporary files.

In the @{i}Misc@{ui} field you can set up many features of Bomb!:

- @{i}Create replies area:@{ui} If this flag is set, an
  @{"area" link area_risposte} named '_exported_' will be created, which will hold
  a copy of all messages written by the user and then exported.

- @{i}Style highlighting:@{ui} This allows you to set/unset the default highlighting
  of stiles (*bold*, /italic/, ecc..)

- @{i}Automatic excess message deletion:@{ui} If this flag is set, Bomb! will
  check for the presence of excess messages every time you quit the program
  and, if required, will @{"erase" link cancellazione} them. If it is not set,
  you will have to start the cleanup manually.

- @{i}Delete packet after importing:@{ui} If this flag is set, the packet
  containing the imported messages will be deleted when Bomb! is done
  importing. In addition, if the @{i}No requester@{ui} flag is set, Bomb!
  will not ask for confirmation before deletint the packet.

- @{i}Reply prefix:@{ui} This is the prefix to be put before the subject of
  messages written in response to other ones. Bomb! can detect if the
  subject already has a reply prefix, to avoid things like Re:Re:Re:Re:Re:...
@endnode

@node default_aree "Area defaults"
The @{i}Max  mess.@{ui} slider and checkmark are used to configure the
excess message @{"deletion" link cancellazione}. The slider allows you to decide the
default value for the number of messages which can be allowed in an area
before deletion starts; the checkmark decides whether the areas should or
not be considered when counting the messages.

The @{i}Learn user list@{ui} checkmark decides whether the areas should by
default contribute to the creation of the @{"user list" link lista_utenti}. This list is unique
for each BBS.

The underlying cycle gadget chooses the default @{"navigation" link GR_grp_7} method
(sequential or tree mode).

The three string gadgets beneath are used to choose the files which contain,
respectively, heading and signature and the default @{"tagline" link fortag} file.
@endnode

@node compressori "Decrunchers setup"
This page determines Bomb!'s behaviour when importing compressed packets.

4 predefined decrunchers are present; top to bottom, these are:
@{i}LhA@{ui},  @{i}LZX@{ui},  @{i}Zip@{ui} and @{i}Arj@{ui}), whose identification parameters cannot
be altered; there are also another two, called @{i}Custom1@{ui} and @{i}Custom2@{ui},
which allow the user to handle particular cases. The Arj format is currently
inactive.

The fields have the following meanings:

- @{i}Name: @{ui}Name of the compression format.

- @{i}Identification string: @{ui}This field holds a string which is used to
  identify the compression format used; this was preferred  over  the  more
  used  method  to  examine the file extension, since sometimes this is not
  the default one for that compression format  (for  example,  QWK  packets
  have  (often  the  QWK  extension,  independently  from their compression
  format).

  If string contains non printable characters,  you  can  enter  it  as  an
  hexadecimal  string,  with  the  format  $xxxxxx, where x are hexadecimal
  digit. If the string contains  a  $  character,  you  must  enter  it  in
  hexadecimal format.

- @{i}Offset: @{ui}This field contains the offset, with respect to the file start,
  where the @{i}identification string@{ui} is found.

- @{i}Command:  @{ui}Packet decompression command; the full path must be
  inserted. @{b}%f@{ub} indicates the file to be decrunched and
  @{b}%d@{ub} the destination directory.

  @{b}Examples: @{ub}LhA -X x %f %d
            Unzip %f -d %d
@endnode

@node configUU&PGP "UUdecode&PGP"
The upper part contains 3 string gadgets which must contain, top to bottom,
the @{"UUencoding" link UUencode} and the @{"UUdecoding" link UUdecode} commands and
the directory to extract '@{"UUdecoded" link UUdecode} files to.

The lower part is used to configure PGP. The @{i}Use PGP password @{ui} checkmark
enables PGP @{"encrypted" link criptazione} messages decrypting; the password
must be inserted in the string gadged. This feature must be used with care,
since it is a weak point in the safety offered by PGP: the password, in fact,
must be saved in Bomb!'s settings, where it is unsafe if anybody else
can access your computer. Password encrypting upon settings saving will be
implemented in a future version of Bomb!.

Finally, the string gadget in the bottom part of the window is used to
choose the file containing your @{"public key" link criptazione}. Bomb!
will extract it from this file whenever it is to be added at the end of a
mesage. You should generate the key using the command @{b}PGP -kxa@{ub},
that is in ASCII mode, to avoid various kinds of problems.
@endnode

@node lista "User list"
Bomb! can keep a user list for each BBS. This list is unique for each BBS.
It can be accessed and edited through the menu item @{i}User list@{ui}.

If you set the @{i}Learn user list@{ui} checkmark in the @{"Area configuration" link WI_label_10} window, when the messages
in that area are read the senders' names will be automatically inserted into
the user list.

The user list can also be accessed from the @{"Write message" link WI_label_6} window to
choose the message addressees. You can, in fact, send a message to multiple
users simply clicking with your mouse.

On the left is the user list, while on the right is the list of the message
addressees (which is initially empty). Clicking on a name in the user list
will add that name to the addressee list. The @{i}Clean@{ui} button will
clear this list.

When you exit this window using the @{i}OK@{ui} button, if at least two
addressees were selected, the @{i}Copies@{ui} checkmark will be set, to
remind you that the message will be sent to multiple addressees. If you
deselect it, the message will be sent to a single addressee.
@endnode

@NODE WI_label_17 "User list configuration"
This window contains a list of user names. This list can be created
automatically (enabling the Learn checkmark in the area confirugation
window) but can also be manually altered using the @{i}Add@{ui} string
field, which adds a name to the list, and the @{i}Remove@{ui} button,
which will remove one.

Clicking on OK will save the modified list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_label_7 "Editor & Quoting"
The @{i}editor@{ui} field allows you to choose the editor you will use,
either by entering its name or using the file requester, while in the @{i}options@{ui}
fieldl you can write the arguments the editor is to be called with.

@{b}Example:@{ub} You can choose GoldED as your text editor; in this case, the
editor field could contain the name of the quickstarter 'GED', and the options field could
contain the string 'STICKY CONFIG bomb.prefs'.

Who wants to use CED instead should write 'KeepIO' in the @{i}options@{ui} field
(see below).

NOTE: Do not use editors which 'detach' themselves after being started (you
can tell this if you get back the prompt after starting the editor from the
CLI). Anyway, usually self-detaching editors have a STICKY option (as in the
example with GoldED's quickstarter).

In the @{i}Quoting@{ui} field you can insert the quoting character; you can also
choose whether to use the initials of the message sender. There is also a
cycle gadget which lets you choose the highlighting style of quoted text;
if you choose a color highlighting you can also choose the number of the
system pen to use. You can also choose the column to wrap the text at when
the quoted text is reformatted. Finally, in the @{i}Snip text@{ui} text
gadget you can insert a string (typically something like [snip]) which will
be inserted in the message instead of the skipped parts when you quote only
a part of the text.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_label_8 "Export"
This command opens a window containing a list of messages to  be  exported.
In  a  future  release  it will be possible to selectively export messages.
Clicking on the Export button the export filter  will  be  activated.

You  can remove a message from the list using the Remove button.

Another useful function enables you to re-edit a message before you  export
it, just in case you've made a mistake or changed your mind.
See @{"message reedit" link reediting}
@ENDNODE

@NODE WI_label_9 "Search"
In this window you can find:

- A group of radio buttons. You can use them to restrict the search to:

  - current area;
  - current BBS;
  - all BBSes.

- A checkmark to search for marked messages.

- 4 checkmarks to allow search in the various fields of the message (you
  can select any number of these).

- A string gadget where you can type the string to search for.

- A checkmark to make the search case sensitive.

- A @{i}Search@{ui} button: by pressing it you start the search of the string
  When the search operation stops, the @{" message list" link WI_label_13} will be displayed.
  This list shows the messages in which the string was found.

- A @{i}List@{ui} button: by pressing it you can display the @{" message list" link WI_label_13}

- A @{i}Close@{ui} button, to terminate search operations.
