@NODE intestazione "Header file"
Usually you need two header files: one is used when you reply to a  message
and  the other when you write a new message. We will call them header-reply
and header-new respectively.

Header file format is as following:

<header.reply>
#
<header.new>

where <header.reply> and <header.new> are two ASCII texts of arbitrary
length. These texts can contain some special character sequences, which
will be expanded as follows:

%f  -  Will be expanded with the name of the addressee (either  the  writer
       of  the  message  you  are  replying  to or the addressee of the new
       message you are writing).

%f1 -  Will be expanded with the first word of the name of  the  addressee.
       This is usually his first name.

%f2 -  Will be expanded with the second word of the name of the  addressee.
       This is usually his last name.

%t  -  Will be expanded with the name of  name  of  the  addressee  of  the
       message you are replying to.

%t1 -  Will be expanded with the first word of %t (see also %f1).

%t2 -  Will be expanded with the second word of %t (see also %f2).

%d  -  Will be expanded with the date of the message you are replying to.

%a  -  Will be expanded with the area name.

%m  -  Will be expanded with the message number.

%o  -  Will be expanded with the message subject.


Here is a little example of a header file:

Hi %f, speaking about %o in area %a
you told to %t
#
Hi %f,

I think it should be quite easy...
@ENDNODE

@node decriptazione "PGP decrpytion"
This menu item replace a PGP encrpyted message with its decrypted  version.
PGP  itself  will  open  a window to request pass phrase; if the message is
only signed, PGP will report if signature is valid. If message  contains  a
public key, it will be extracted.

If encrypted section is headed or followed by a plain text, this last  will
be lost.

Password won't be asked if it has been entered in the proper string  gadget
in @{"global preferences" link WI_label_18}.

CAUTION ! Entering you pass phrase in Bomb! is VERY dangerous, since  Bomb!
settings file is NOT encrypted.

To use PGP-related functions, you must  have  PGP  in  your  C:  directory;
alternatively, you can create in C: a link to PGP.
@endnode

@node criptazione "PGP encrypting"
In the "Write message" window there are 4 PGP-related gadgets:

- @{i}Sign@{ui}: Sign message with user key.

- @{i}Encrypt@{ui}: Encrypt message with addressee public key.

- @{i}Clearsig@{ui}: Sign message with flag '-clearsig=on'.

- @{i}Add public key@{ui}: Add user public key at the end of message:
                  file containing public key can be selected in
                  @{"Global Configuration" link WI_label_18} window.

Message will be encrypted on editor exit;  PGP  will  open  its  window  to
request password or to display errors. If you want to add a plain text, you
can @{i}Reedit@{ui} you message from export window.
@endnode

@node UUdecode "UUdecode"
If message contains an UUencoded file,  you  can  decode  it  by  selecting
@{i}UUdecode@{ui} menu item. File will be extracted in the directory you have
selected in @{"Global settings" link WI_label_18}.

In @{"Global settings" link WI_label_18} you can also choose which program you want to use to
UUdecode: you must specify whole command line, including path if it is  not
in C:; you can use %f and %d in place of filename and directory.

@{b}Example:@{ub} If you use UUxt, you can input something like this:

UUxt x %f dest=%d

You can UUdecode a file even from Message list window. If you do this,  you
can  take  advantage of the "Join & Decode" feature: if file is splitted in
more than one uuencoded message, just select all of them and then click  on
UUdecode button; all selected message will be joined and the resulting will
be UUdecoded.
@endnode

@node UUencode "UUencode"
In the "Write message" window, you can select a file to be UUencoded and
joined at the and of your message. You must have configured correctly Bomb!
on which UUencoder you want to use. See also @{"UUdecode" link UUdecode}).
@endnode

@node autoextract "Automatic message packets unarchiving"
Bomb! can recognize compressed message packets and call proper  unarchiver;
In  @{"Global settings" link WI_label_18} you can find a page where you can
configure this feature @{"Unarchiver" link compressori}.
@endnode

@node autoimport "Importazione automatica dei pacchetti di messaggi"
Bomb  can  automatically  import  message  packet;  this  function  can  be
activated  in  the  configuration window of the BBS by acting on the proper
checkmark. In the string gadget you must input an  AmigaDOS-style  template
(i.e. something like #?.qwk).

Bomb! will search in the import path all files matching the given template;
if only one file is found, it will be immedately imported, otherwise a file
requester will be shown, allowing to choose a file.
@endnode

@node reediting "Messages reediting"
From the @{"Export" link WI_label_8} window you can reedit a message before actually
exporting it. You can do this by simply selecting it and  clicking  on  the
Reedit gadget; you can change addressee, subject, append an UUencoded file,
encrypt message, append a plain section to a previously  encrypted  message
and, obviously, modify message body.
@endnode

@node salvataggio "Saving messages on file"
You can save messages on a file. This function can be activated by pressing
the proper gadget in the @{"Print" link WI_label_14} window or in the various list
windows.

When you press the button, a requester will show up asking the name of  the
save file.
@endnode

@node area_risposte "Exported messages area"
You can have an area where are stored copies of messages you have exported;
this  can  be  useful if you happen to lose a packet. You can activate this
feature by setting  the  @{i}Create  replies  area@{ui}  checkmark  in  the
@{"Global settings" link WI_label_18} window.

If you happen to lose a message, simply find it into this area, then select
@{i}Re-Export@{ui} menu item; this will create a copy of selected message in the
export list.

In this area the @{i}From@{ui} field contains the area to which the message was
directed; the sender is (obviously) the user itself.
@endnode

