@NODE pop3impmain "Pop3.imp"

    Version 2.1 (30 Settembre 1996)

    This filter allows you to import messages from a server supporting POP3
    format.  You  need a TCP/IP stack. Pop3.imp has been tested with AmiTCP
    (version 4.0+) and with Miami (every version).

    To configure filter you don't need to have an active TCP/IP stack.

    In order to simplify message replying, ReplyTo field, if present,  will
    be used insted of From field as sender address.

                @{" Configuration      " link pop3impconfig}
                @{" Other informations " link pop3impinfo}
                @{" Bugs               " link pop3impbug}
                @{" Author             " link pop3impautore}

@ENDNODE

@NODE pop3impconfig "Pop3.imp configuration"

    Configuration window is  split  in  three  part:  Network,  Header  and
    Special.

                @{" Network  " link pop3imprete}
                @{" Header   " link pop3imphead}
                @{" Special  " link pop3impspec}

    On the bottom there are two buttons:

    - @{B}Save@{UB}
        Save settings and exit.

    - @{B}Cancella@{UB}
        Exit without saving.

@ENDNODE

@NODE pop3imprete "Network settings"

    - @{B}Host Name@{UB}
        Here you can input the name of the host  from  which  you  want  to
        receive messages.

    - @{B}User Name@{UB}
        Here you can input the name with which you are  known  on  selected
        host: usually it is your login name.

    - @{B}Password@{UB}
        Here you can input your password.

    - @{B}Delete msg ?@{UB}
        Set this checkmark if you want that host delete messages after  you
        have read them.

    - @{B}Verbose mode ?@{UB}
        Set this checkmark if you want that pop3.imp show some informations
        during import. This can be useful if you have problems.

@ENDNODE

@NODE pop3imphead "Header settings"

    - @{B}Keep whole header@{UB}
        Header contains various fields, such as  sender,  addressee,  date,
        subject,  reply-to,  etc. etc. If you set this checkmark, the whole
        header will be kept together with message body.  Usually  it's  not
        useful to activate this option.

    It's usually more useful to keep selected fields of the header.

    - @{B}To@{UB}
        Keep addressee address ;))).

    - @{B}From@{UB}
        Keep sender address.

    - @{B}Date@{UB}
        Keep date.

    - @{B}Subject@{UB}
        Keep subject.

    - @{B}Message-ID@{UB}
        Keep Message-ID.

    - @{B}Reply-To@{UB}
        Keep Reply-To address.

    If you have any doubt or if you want to know more, see @{"Message format" link pop3formato}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE pop3impspec "Special settings"

    This configuration page allows to create special areas  where  you  can
    store  messages  coming  from  special addresses. This can be useful to
    store in a separate area all messages coming from a mailing list, or to
    keep all together message coming from a special sender.

    This feature works as follows: you should insert <string,area> pairs in
    proper  list; then you have to choose which fields of the header of the
    incoming message are checked  against  string;  when  pop3.imp  read  a
    message,  scans the area list; for every area, the corresponding string
    is checked against selected fields of the message header. If a match is
    found,  the  message  is stored in current area, otherwise next area is
    checked. If message doesn't belong to  any  area,  it  is  assigned  to
    e-mail area.

    The third column of the listview (titled TFSR) shows  which  fields  of
    the  message  header  (To,  From,  Subj  &  RepTo respectively) will be
    checked against string.

    For example, you can input following area:

        Sender: mui           Area: MUI-List        Fields:TF R
        Sender: real-list     Area: Real3D          Fields:TFS
        Sender: md1458        Area: Luca            Fields: F
        Sender: giacomo@fel   Area: Giacomo         Fields: F R

    If you have any doubt or need other informations, see @{"Message format" link pop3formato}.

    - @{B}Sender@{UB}
        Here you can input the string that will be searched in Reply-To (if
        exists) or From field.

    - @{B}Area@{UB}
        Here you can input the name of the area associated to currently
        selected sender.

    - @{B}To@{UB}
        Check string against To field.

    - @{B}From@{UB}
        Check string against From field.

    - @{B}Subj@{UB}
        Check string against Subj field.

    - @{B}RepTo@{UB}
        Check string against ReplyTo field.

    - @{B}Add@{UB}
        Adds currently selected <sender,area> pair to the list.

    - @{B}Remove@{UB}
        Remove currently selected <sender,area> pair from the list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE pop3formato "Message format"

    Messages received from a POP3 compliant server have  a  structure  like
    this:

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
From l.desantis@hella.stm.it Tue, 20 Feb 96 22:32:50
Received: from urano.inet.it (urano.inet.it [194.20.8.1]) by agora.stm.it (8.6.8.1/8.6.6) with ESMTP id UAA20937 for <l.desanti
s@agora.stm.it>; Tue, 20 Feb 1996 20:15:22 GMT
Received: from amp (amp.flashnet.it [194.21.12.230]) by urano.inet.it (8.6.12/8.6.12) with SMTP id UAA04182 for <l.desantis@ago
ra.stm.it>; Tue, 20 Feb 1996 20:15:14 +0100
Received: by amp.flashnet.it (Amiga SMTPpost 1.04 December 9, 1994)
id AA01; Tue, 20 Feb 96 20:16:44 CET
Received: by amp.flashnet.it (Amiga SMTPpost 1.04 December 9, 1994)
id AA01; Tue, 20 Feb 96 20:09:14 CET
Subject: Prova2
From: Alberto_Caporro@amp.flashnet.it (Alberto Caporro)
Date: Tue, 20 Feb 96 20:09:14 CET
Organization: AMP-BBS
Message-ID: <19960220.7554CF0.11E31@amp.flashnet.it>
To: l.desantis@agora.stm.it
Reply-To: alberto_caporro@amp.flashnet.it

Ecco la prova numero 2....va tutto bene ?

-- Via DLG Pro v1.0

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

    The first section (up  to  blank  row)  is  the  so-called  header:  it
    contains  a number of information fields regarding the message (sender,
    addressee, subject and so on) and the path followed in its "travel".

    Nearly all of these fields are quiet useless, so pop3.imp allows you to
    filter out this section. See also @{"Header" link pop3imphead}.

    However, if you prefer, you can keep important fields (From, To, Date,
