@NODE filos "Working philosophy"

Bomb! was born as a single-application program, to off-line read message of
my  favourite  BBS: AMP (Amiga Meeting Point). During development I decided
to implement a system of import-export  filters.  This  makes  possible  to
read-write message in a number of format: all you need is proper filter (or
filter pair).

Only later I have added filters such as SMTP and POP3, that allows  you  to
read-write messages via Internet.

Thus you shouldn't wonder if some terms seem a little  unusual,  especially
if you use it only as an Internet e-mail manager.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Bomb! if a multiformat offline reader (OLR); it allows to have an unlimited
number  of  'mailboxes'.  These  mailbox  are called 'BBS': each of them is
associated to a particulare 'message source' (i.e. your favourite BBS,  you
Internet provider, etc.). Each BBS has its own configuration and filters.

So a 'BBS' can be an actual BBS, your e-mail mailbox or something other.

Every BBS contains a number of 'areas':  this  is  due  to  the  fact  that
usually  BBS's message base is composed of various areas, each related to a
particular topic.

This structure could seem useless for an e-mail  mailbox.  Well,  it  isn't
actually  so;  using  POP3 filter you can sort incoming message in separate
areas, keeping distinct messages coming from different senders. Using  this
feature  you  can  have,  for  example,  a  separate  area  for each fo the
mailing-lists you have subscribed.

If you want to know more about Bomb! and its advanced features, please read
manual section @{"Program usage" link uso}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE quick2 "Quickstart: QWK bbs"

Start using Bomb! couldn't be simpler, even if you're not a Guru.  All  you
need  is  some  easy  configuration,  and  then  you can start reading your
messages.

First you need to create a BBS. If no one  exists  yet,  upon  start  Bomb!
automatically  opens BBS configuration window, otherwise you can open it by
selecting "Configuration - BBS" menu item.

You can add a BBS by simply typing the name you want for it in the Add text
gadget and pressing RETURN. BBS name will show up in the list.

Now you choose BBS packets format; this requires that you select import and
export filters, which usually have an auto-explicative name, with a .imp or
.exp extension. If your BBS uses QWK format for its  mail,  you  will  need
qwk.imp  and  qwk.exp  filters.  You  can select them by clicking on proper
gadgets on the right of text gadgets and selecting desired filter from  the
file  requester  that will show up. Now you need to configure filters: this
can be  done  by  clicking  Configure  gadget;  this  simple  operation  is
explained in detail in every filter manual.

Remaining part of this window is used to configure auto import feature,  so
you don't need at this time.

If you want to configure other BBSes, you can repeat above steps.

Now select "Configuration - Global" menu item; from resulting window select
"Editor  &  Quoting" page. In the "Editor" text gadget you should input the
name of the editor you want to use; if it isn't in  th  C:  directory,  you
MUST  specify  all  path.  For  example,  if  you want to use GoldEd, whose
quickstarter Ged is in C: directory, simply  type  "ged"  (without  quotes,
obviously);  if you want to use system editor, input "ed". In the following
line, labelled Options, you  should  input  every  option  needed  by  your
editor;  for  example  GoldEd  requires STICKY keyword to avoid it detaches
from the calling process.

Now select "Area defaults" page. Check "Max mess."  gadget,  so  that  read
message  exceeding  user  defined limit can be removed.To remove them, just
select "Special - BBS cleanup" menu  item.  Cleanup  process  can  be  made
automatic:  you  find  how to do this elsewhere in this manual. If you want
you can choose "Tree" as default navigation mode: by doing this you will be
able to read messages following their father-son links.

Finally, since BBSes usually compress their message packets,  you  need  to
install, if they are not present, required unarchivers, depending on format
used by your BBS. If they're not in C: directory,  you  should  tell  Bomb!
where it can find them; you can do this by selecting "Unarchivers" page and
editing proper fields; beware not to  delete  any  flag  present  on  these
lines, since they're are need for correct operation.

Now you can import your first packet. Select "Message - Import" menu  item.
A  requester  will  show up, where you can choose file to import. Archiving
format will be automatically detected, and packet will  be  unarchived  and
imported.

Now you can read messages using simple navigation commands.  To  know  more
about  these  and  more  advanced features of Bomb!, you should read entire
manual.

@ENDNODE

