@NODE quick1 "Quickstart: internet mail"

Start using Bomb! it's really very simple, even  for  unexperienced  users.
All  you  have  to  do  is  some simple configuration, and you can start to
import message packets.

First you have to create a BBS. If no BBS is present, on startup Bomb! will
automatically  display  the  BBS  Configuration  window; otherwise, you can
access it by menu (Configuration - BBS)

To add a BBS you only need to type the BBS name in the  "Add"  text  gadget
and press RETURN. The BBS name will show up in the top-left listview.

Now you have to select import and export filters: in  this  case  you  will
select,  respectively,  "pop3.imp"  and  "smtp.exp";  you  can  do  this by
clicking on the pop-up gadgets that are on the right of the  text  gadgets.
Next  you have to configure filters; this is simply done by clicking on the
"Configure" gadget. You can find how to configure filters in the  "Filters"
section of this manual.

The other gadgets in the window are related to the automatic packet  import
function;  we  will  ignore  them,  since  e-mail  filters  don't need this
feature.

If you want to configure other BBSes, you can repeat all  steps;  otherwise
you can go further.

Now select menu item "Settings - Global", and then, in the window that will
show  up,  select  "Editor  & Quoting". In the "Editor" text gadget you can
type the name of the  editor  of  your  choice.  If  it  isn't  in  the  C:
directory, you will have to insert the complete path to it. For example, if
you want to use GoldEd (whose quickstarter GED is in the C: directory), you
simply type "ged" (no quotes). If you prefer the system editor ED, you will
type "ed" (again, no quotes). In the following gadget, named "Options", you
have  to type the arguments for your editor, if needed; for example, GoldEd
requires the STICKY option, to prevent detaching from the calling process.

Now select "Area defaults". Check "Max mess." gadget; in this way exceeding
messages  can  be  deleted.  To  delete  them,  select  "BBS  cleanup" from
"Special" menu. The cleanup process can be made  automatic  (you  can  find
elsewhere  how  to  do  this).  If  you  like  it,  you  can  select  "Tree
navigation": this will allow you to read  messages  following  the  thread,
instead of the simple numerical order.

Now you can try to import your  first  packet.  Select  "Import"  from  the
"Messages"  menu. The import filter will open a status window, showing some
text that allow you to control the operation. Should occur  an  error,  the
filter  will  show  an  error  code  and some text; if you want to do a bug
report, please state as much informations as possible.

If filter ended its operations normally, you can finally read your messages
and navigate between them using the navigation commands. To know more about
this (and about a lot of other feature of Bomb!) it is recommended that you
read the rest of this manual carefully.

To fully exploit all features of the POP3 import filter (such  as  the  the
sorting  feature,  that  enables  you  to  have separate areas for messages
coming from separate senders), it is recommended that  you  read  carefully
the @{" POP3 filter manual " link pop3impmain}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE menu_header "Header"

Usually Bomb! tries not to show the e-mail header  of  message,  if  it  is
present.  If  you  want  to  show  it,  you can use this menu item: this is
ghosted when message hase no e-mail header, and becomes unghosted  when  it
has one, allowing you to display it.

Bomb! recognize an e-mail header by searching for a row beginning with  the
string  "Message-ID".  If there is no such line, this menu item will remain
ghosted.

@ENDNODE

